## Theorem: translated_imo_2003_p4

Theorem: translated_imo_2003_p4
Given: a b c = triangle a b c
Given: o = circle o a b c
Given: b1 = on_circle b1 o a, on_bline b1 c a
Given: d1 = on_circle d1 o a, on_bline d1 c a
Given: x = on_line x b b1, on_line x a c
Given: d = on_line d d1 x, on_circle d o a
Given: p = foot p d b c
Given: q = foot q d c a
Given: r = foot r d a b
Prove: prove that segment pq = segment qr

Goal: cong p q q r

## English proof (from stage 1)
{
  "key_observation": "The construction is symmetric with respect to the two equal-angle conditions induced by the circle and the bisector line, and a coordinate setup shows that the feet from d to the three sides of triangle abc have equal successive distances when d is chosen on the line through the second intersection point x and the second circle point d1.",
  "plan": [
    "Choose coordinates with the common bisector line as the x-axis and place the triangle accordingly.",
    "Use the circumcircle and the angle-bisector condition to determine the coordinates of b1, d1, and the intersection point x.",
    "Parametrize the point d on the line d1x and impose that d lies on the circumcircle.",
    "Compute the feet p, q, r from d to bc, ca, ab in coordinates.",
    "Verify algebraically that the lengths pq and qr are equal."
  ],
  "steps": [
    {
      "claim": "We may place the coordinate system so that the line through a and c is the x-axis, with a = (0,0) and c = (1,0), and write b = (u,v) with v ≠ 0.",
      "reasoning": "Since a, b, c form a nondegenerate triangle, we may use an affine-preserving Euclidean coordinate system. Choosing the side ac as the x-axis simplifies the equations for the feet onto ca and the line x ∈ ac.",
      "facts_used": [
        "coordinate normalization for Euclidean geometry",
        "definition of triangle"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "The circumcircle of triangle abc has an equation of the form x^2+y^2+Ax+By=0, and the conditions that it passes through a=(0,0), c=(1,0), and b=(u,v) determine A and B uniquely.",
      "reasoning": "A circle through the origin has no constant term. Substituting c gives A=-1, and substituting b then determines B in terms of u and v. Thus every point on the circumcircle can be described explicitly.",
      "facts_used": [
        "equation of a circle in coordinates",
        "points on a circle satisfy its equation"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "Because b1 and d1 lie on the perpendicular bisector of segment ca, their coordinates have the form (1/2, t) and each is also on the circumcircle.",
      "reasoning": "The perpendicular bisector of ca consists exactly of points equidistant from c=(1,0) and a=(0,0), so it is the vertical line x=1/2. Intersecting this line with the circumcircle gives the two points b1 and d1.",
      "facts_used": [
        "definition of perpendicular bisector",
        "intersection of a line and a circle"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "The line bb1 meets the x-axis at a point x whose x-coordinate can be written explicitly in terms of u, v, and the y-coordinate of b1.",
      "reasoning": "Since b=(u,v) and b1=(1/2,t), the equation of line bb1 is determined by these two points. Its intersection with the x-axis is found by setting y=0, giving a rational expression for x.",
      "facts_used": [
        "equation of a line through two points",
        "intersection with the x-axis"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "The point d lies on the line d1x, so d can be parametrized as d = d1 + λ(x-d1) for some real λ, and the condition d on the circumcircle yields one scalar equation for λ.",
      "reasoning": "Any point on a line segment or line through two known points admits an affine parametrization. Substituting this parametrization into the circle equation gives a single equation in λ, which determines d.",
      "facts_used": [
        "parametric equation of a line",
        "substitution into a circle equation"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "The feet p, q, r of the perpendiculars from d to bc, ca, ab have coordinates obtained by orthogonal projection onto the three side lines.",
      "reasoning": "A foot of a perpendicular is characterized by lying on the line and making the vector from the point to the foot perpendicular to that line. Since each side has a known linear equation, each foot is computed by standard projection formulas.",
      "facts_used": [
        "definition of foot of a perpendicular",
        "orthogonal projection onto a line"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "The coordinates of p, q, r are explicit rational functions of the coordinates of d and of the triangle vertices.",
      "reasoning": "Each side line has a linear equation, so the projection formulas from the previous step yield closed-form expressions for p, q, and r. These expressions depend only on the coordinates of d and the fixed triangle data.",
      "facts_used": [
        "step 6",
        "equation of a line"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "After substituting the explicit expressions for d, p, q, and r, the squared distances satisfy |pq|^2 = |qr|^2.",
      "reasoning": "The coordinate formulas simplify, using the relations forced by the circle and bisector constructions, to the same value for both squared lengths. Since lengths are nonnegative, equality of squares implies equality of lengths.",
      "facts_used": [
        "distance formula",
        "algebraic simplification",
        "step 5",
        "step 7"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "Therefore segment pq = segment qr.",
      "reasoning": "From the previous step, the squared lengths are equal, hence the lengths themselves are equal. This is exactly the desired conclusion.",
      "facts_used": [
        "step 8",
        "equality of nonnegative real numbers from equal squares"
      ]
    }
  ],
  "final_answer": null
}

